I base my prediction entirely on the psychology of John Kasich. There is no reason to believe that his performance (or the performance of others) will have any impact on his decision to remain in the race. As it stands now, Kasich still has fewer delegates than Marco Rubio and even came in 4th place behind Rubio in the Arizona primary a week after Rubio suspended his campaign. Kasich has not won any delegates since this became a three-person race. Kasich has continued to underperform in recent primaries. Kasich has little money and organization and has no national campaign apparatus. There is no reason to believe that Kasich's decision to remain in the race or to suspend his campaign is in any way tied to his performance in any primary contest. He has no mathematical path to the nomination, he can only hope for a brokered/contested convention.

I love this question. I've been thinking about it a lot lately. As of 3/29/16, many top operatives and Kasich himself believe that he has the best chance of Republicans in the general election. In order for Trump to win on the first ballot, he would need in excess of 55% of the remaining delegates, which is highly improbable given his rising unfavorable ratings in polls since the primaries began and his recent attacks on Cruz' wife. If Trump does not win on the first ballot, the delegates are free to switch to another candidate. Top party operatives seem crystal-clear on this scenario as does Kasich. The only reason I'm not 90% is that Kasich says he won't drop out "before Wisconsin". I'm concerned that he's not stating more confidence about hanging in there than that statement implies. His motivation for staying in is exceedingly high. Dropping out before the convention would be a baffling move that would throw the party into a state of near despair. It's certainly not impossible, and money may determine the outcome, but it would go down as one of the great fumbles in American political history.

As with Cruz, there's no case for Kasich to drop out prior to New York. Unlike Cruz, though, there may be a case for Kasich to drop out prior to New York. For example, if the race in California were to narrow to a two-way race between Trump and Cruz, with Trump holding a narrow plurality and Kasich in a distant third but with enough votes to sway the outcome, it may emerge that Kasich's best shot at winning the nomination would come by ceding California to ensure a brokered convention. However, it seems more likely that in this case Kasich would make certain strategic moves (as Rubio did in Ohio) to push his delegates to Cruz without dropping off the ballot entirely. His post-California scenario is identical to Cruz's: If Trump has the nomination sown up, it's all over; if not he goes to the convention.

Before the NY primary, there are 3 republican contests: AZ, UT, WI. In order for Kasich to stay in the race, I think he must win Wisconsin to make his case that he can stop Trump from amassing a majority of delegates. That said, there is no recent polling of WI - the last poll (2/18-2/21) included Carson, Rubio and Bush (http://fox6now.com/2016/02/25/new-marquette-university-law-school-poll/). Let's assume the race is a toss-up between Trump and Kasich in WI. Losing all 3 primaries before NY will likely entail the end of the Kasich campaign (though there is always a chance he somehow convinces himself to stay in). I therefore estimate his chances of dropping out before NY as 40%.

Kasich is likely to do best in states that vote later, and his strategy is to present himself as an alternative to the "outsider" candidates Trump and Cruz. That strategy hasn't been working well recently, but a win in NY, NJ and CA could make that more presentable. He could also have some leverage at the convention by remaining in the race and controlling delegates.
